                [
                    _t('Central Idea Across a Whole Work', 'A literary work\'s central idea (its complex claim about human experience) is not stated once but built cumulatively across all its parts: character arcs, plot structure, imagery patterns, point of view, setting, and language all contribute to the unified argument.', 'The central idea of a novel or play is not its "lesson" or moral — it is the complex, specific claim about human experience that emerges from all of the work\'s literary choices working together; it cannot be reduced to a cliché.', 'FRQ 3: write a thesis that identifies the specific central idea of a self-chosen work and argues how a specific literary element develops it.'),
                    _t('How Parts Serve the Whole', 'Every significant literary choice in a work — character, setting, structure, language — contributes to the work\'s unified meaning; the best literary analysis explains how parts serve the whole rather than treating elements in isolation.', 'Analyzing a literary element in isolation ("the author uses imagery") without connecting it to the work\'s central idea produces description, not literary analysis; strong analysis always shows how the part contributes to the whole.', 'FRQ 3: explain how a specific literary choice — not just what it is, but how it contributes to the work\'s central idea — constitutes the essay\'s line of reasoning.'),
                    _t('Authorial Choice and Intention', 'Literary analysis attributes choices to authors, not characters: "the writer uses dramatic irony to..." rather than "Hamlet decides to..."; this framing keeps the analysis focused on how the work creates meaning through craft.', 'Analyzing characters as if they are real people ("Hamlet should have...") confuses fictional people with literary constructions; skilled literary analysis focuses on what the author achieves through the construction of characters, not what characters "really" wanted.', 'FRQ: practice framing claims as authorial choices: "By [literary choice], [writer] develops [aspect of central idea]."'),
                ],
                ['central idea', 'unified argument', 'authorial choice', 'whole-work analysis', 'literary argument'],
                ['Articulate a work\'s central idea as a complex, specific claim about human experience', 'Explain how individual literary elements contribute to the work\'s unified argument', 'Frame literary analysis in terms of authorial choices, not character psychology'],
