                    ('The difference between a theme and a central idea in literary analysis is:', ['Central idea is a specific, arguable claim about the theme\'s subject; a theme is a broad topic area', 'They are synonymous terms in AP® Literary analysis', 'A theme is specific; a central idea is general', 'A central idea is stated explicitly; a theme is always implicit']),
                    ('Analyzing how "parts serve the whole" in a literary work means:', ['Explaining how each literary choice contributes to the work\'s unified argument or central idea', 'Summarizing each chapter or scene and noting its contribution to the plot', 'Analyzing each literary element separately and then listing them at the end', 'Focusing on the beginning and ending of the work as the most important parts']),
                    ('Framing literary analysis as "authorial choices" rather than character decisions is important because:', ['It keeps the analysis focused on how the work creates meaning through craft rather than treating fictional people as real', 'It is more polite to the characters in the work', 'Literary characters should never be quoted directly in essays', 'Authorial choice framing is required by the AP® rubric explicitly']),
                    ('A literary argument about a whole work is most persuasive when:', ['It shows how multiple literary choices work together to develop a specific, complex central idea', 'It focuses on the single most important scene in the work', 'It agrees with the most respected critical interpretation of the work', 'It covers the entire plot in chronological order before making a claim']),
